    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix seq_arr_front() behavior with empty arrays and memory corruption\n\n### Summary\nWhen calling seq_arr_front() on certain seq_arr instances, the returned pointer does not behave as expected during iteration. This manifests as incorrect loop termination or segfaults when dereferencing the iterator.\n\n### Changes\n- `common/utils/ds/seq_arr.c`: Fixed memory allocation bug in maybe_shrink() that was causing corruption\n- `common/utils/ds/seq_arr.c`: Added NULL check assertion in seq_arr_front() for consistency\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Create a seq_arr and populate with 100+ elements\n2. Erase enough elements to trigger the shrink path in maybe_shrink()\n3. Call seq_arr_front() and attempt to iterate through the array\n4. Observe incorrect iteration behavior or crashes when accessing elements\n\nThe root cause was that calloc was allocating cap*cap bytes instead of cap*element_size bytes during array shrink operations, leading to memory corruption that manifested when accessing elements through the front iterator.\n"
}